-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Housing Finance and Kenya Power Shares Move
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-09-20T17:34:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/sub-saharan-african-stocks-housing-finance-kenya-power-lighting-move.html

          
          
             Kenya’s  All-Share Index  gained for
a ninth day, the longest winning streak in 15 months, climbing
0.6 percent to 82.3 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. That’s the
highest closing level since July 2008.  
 The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  declined 0.5
percent to 22,879.33 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to
data from the bourse’s website.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  advanced for the first
time in three days, rising 1.4 percent to 786.79 by the 5 p.m.
close in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index 
snapped two days of gains, retreating 0.2 percent to 6,780.83 by
the 3 p.m. close in Accra. Mauritius’s Semdex index dropped 0.5
percent to 1,782.48 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis, data
from the exchange’s  website  show.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Housing Finance Ltd.  (HFCL KN), Kenya’s only publicly
traded mortgage company, climbed 50 cents, or 2 percent, to
25.75 shillings, the highest since Aug. 10. The lender started
selling 5 billion shillings ($62 million) of bonds to increase
credit to its customers. Bids for Housing Finance’s bonds, which
mature in seven years, will close on Oct. 1 while settlement
will take place on Oct. 11, the company said in a statement
published in the Nairobi-based Daily Nation newspaper today.  
 Kenya Power & Lighting Ltd.  (KPLL KN), the country’s only
electricity distributor, rallied 10 shillings, or 4.2 percent,
to 246 shillings, a three-year high. The Kenya Electrical Trades
and Allied Workers Union, which representing 8,000 workers,
canceled a strike planned to start today after brokering a deal
with the company, which agreed to hire more full-time workers,
Secretary-General Ernest Nadome said.  
